# Mission 3 - Federation & Enterprise Applications

## Overview

Mission 3 introduced the core concepts of Identity Engineering by explaining how Microsoft Entra ID authenticates users and how Enterprise Applications trust Microsoft Entra through federation.

Instead of every application maintaining separate usernames and passwords, organizations centralize authentication using Microsoft Entra ID. After successful authentication, Microsoft Entra issues a security token containing claims about the user's identity. Enterprise Applications validate the token and use those claims to determine what the user is authorized to access.

---

# Identity Flow

```
User
   │
   ▼
Microsoft Entra ID
(Authentication)
   │
   ▼
Security Token Issued
   │
   ▼
Claims
(Name, Email, Groups, Roles)
   │
   ▼
Enterprise Application
(Salesforce, ServiceNow, Workday)
   │
   ▼
Authorization
   │
   ▼
Application Access
```

The important lesson from this mission is understanding that Microsoft Entra performs authentication, while the Enterprise Application performs authorization.

---

# Authentication vs Authorization

Authentication answers one question:

> Who are you?

Microsoft Entra verifies the user's identity through credentials, MFA, Conditional Access policies, and other security controls.

Authorization answers another question:

> What are you allowed to do?

Enterprise Applications evaluate the claims contained in the token and determine what resources the authenticated user is permitted to access.

This distinction became one of the most important concepts learned during Mission 3.

---

# Federation

Federation establishes a trust relationship between Microsoft Entra ID and Enterprise Applications.

Instead of storing passwords independently, applications rely on Microsoft Entra to authenticate users.

Benefits include:

- Single Sign-On (SSO)
- Centralized Identity Management
- Simplified User Lifecycle Management
- Reduced Administrative Overhead
- Stronger Security
- Consistent Access Policies
